WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:03.430
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:03.430 --> 00:00:07.690
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: It's a
great honor this afternoon

00:00:07.690 --> 00:00:11.690
to have Laila Lalami here with us,
the author of The Moor's Account,

00:00:11.690 --> 00:00:15.390
but more importantly, you
know, she has many other things

00:00:15.390 --> 00:00:17.960
that she does including she's a
nonfiction essayist who writes

00:00:17.960 --> 00:00:22.370
as a critic at large for the Los
Angeles Times and as a columnist

00:00:22.370 --> 00:00:25.940
for The Nation, so she both is
an incredible imaginative writer

00:00:25.940 --> 00:00:28.860
but also engaged with what's
happening in our world now,

00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:30.750
so welcome to the National
Book Festival.

00:00:30.750 --> 00:00:32.050
&gt;&gt; Laila Lalami: Thank you
very much for having me.

00:00:32.050 --> 00:00:33.890
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: I just want to
say a little bit more about you.

00:00:33.890 --> 00:00:38.830
You were born in Rabat, educated in
Morocco, Great Britain and the US.

00:00:38.830 --> 00:00:41.920
You have recently received
the Guggenheim Fellowship,

00:00:41.920 --> 00:00:43.220
is that right?

00:00:43.220 --> 00:00:44.520 position:56%
And you're working on your new book.

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:48.340
But the Moor's Account which was
your last novel not only was it

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:49.640
listed for the Booker Prize

00:00:49.640 --> 00:00:51.180
but it was a finalist
for the Pulitzer Prize.

00:00:51.180 --> 00:00:53.330
It's been an incredibly
well-received book.

00:00:53.330 --> 00:00:54.940
And I wondered if you
could tell us a little bit

00:00:54.940 --> 00:01:00.410
about the history behind the actual
history that inspired this book.

00:01:00.410 --> 00:01:05.020
&gt;&gt; Laila Lalami: So, some years
ago, I was just reading a book

00:01:05.020 --> 00:01:07.920
about Moorish Spain and
I came across a mention

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:11.980
of a man named Estebanico
who was said

00:01:11.980 --> 00:01:14.910
to be the first black
explorer of America.

00:01:14.910 --> 00:01:17.160
And I though to myself, "What
do you mean first black explorer

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:18.460
of American?"

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:19.760
That it seems like
a fascinating story,

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:21.060
I need to find out more about it.

00:01:21.060 --> 00:01:24.090
And it turns out, he was part
of the Narvaez expedition

00:01:24.090 --> 00:01:26.220
and had been written about by
a man named Cabeza de Vaca.

00:01:26.220 --> 00:01:30.160
And I had heard about Cabeza de
Vaca of course, but I hadn't heard

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:31.930
about this fellow Estebanico.

00:01:31.930 --> 00:01:34.720
And so, that's really
what drew me in.

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:36.670
I was curious to know
more about him.

00:01:36.670 --> 00:01:39.850
And it's really an
absolutely fascinating story.

00:01:39.850 --> 00:01:45.550
So the Narvaez expedition left
Spain in the spring of 1527.

00:01:45.550 --> 00:01:49.610
And after a number of adventures
eventually landed near what is now

00:01:49.610 --> 00:01:54.940
Tampa Bay in Florida
in the spring of 1528.

00:01:54.940 --> 00:01:59.680
And a group of men was sent ashore
to sort of reconnoiter the area,

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:05.010
they had spied an indigenous
village from their ships and so,

00:02:05.010 --> 00:02:09.320
they decided to disembark there
and they were sent to the village

00:02:09.320 --> 00:02:12.520
to reconnoiter, and they
found a little nugget of gold.

00:02:12.520 --> 00:02:16.330
And then Cabeza de Vaca's
relation of the Narvaez expedition,

00:02:16.330 --> 00:02:18.770
that nugget of gold is
described as being small enough

00:02:18.770 --> 00:02:21.950
that it could fit in
a child's rattle.

00:02:21.950 --> 00:02:26.490
And so, because of that, Narvaez
gave the order to disembark

00:02:26.490 --> 00:02:29.950
which is this long process that
involved moving the horses ashore,

00:02:29.950 --> 00:02:33.240
moving all of the supplies
and the 600 people

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:35.010
that were part of that expedition.

00:02:35.010 --> 00:02:38.630 position:56%
And so they spent a few days in that
indigenous village which by the way

00:02:38.630 --> 00:02:40.850
at this point had been
emptied of its inhabitants

00:02:40.850 --> 00:02:43.620
because the people had
spied the ships in their bay

00:02:43.620 --> 00:02:46.740
and they decided very wisely
to flee the village and wait

00:02:46.740 --> 00:02:48.810
and see what these invaders wanted.

00:02:48.810 --> 00:02:50.160
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: And
this is Florida, right?

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:51.470
&gt;&gt; Laila Lalami: Mm-hmm.

00:02:51.470 --> 00:02:54.600
And so they found a few more
traces of gold and at that point,

00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:57.670
Narvaez made a very faithful
decision which is that he decided

00:02:57.670 --> 00:02:59.910
to split the expedition into two.

00:02:59.910 --> 00:03:03.680
And he decided to send a land
contingent inland to go look

00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:06.790
for more gold and to
send the other half

00:03:06.790 --> 00:03:10.020
of the expedition back home
the ships and to go meet them

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:14.810 position:56%
at the nearest Spanish port which he
believed was only 20 leagues away,

00:03:14.810 --> 00:03:16.940
in fact it was more
than 1000 leagues away

00:03:16.940 --> 00:03:19.700
so there was this big
mistake in navigation.

00:03:19.700 --> 00:03:24.020
The navigation was not yet
an exact science at the time.

00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:28.700
And so, these men, they all decide
to go inland to look for gold

00:03:28.700 --> 00:03:31.210
and it seems kind of crazy when
we think about it today like,

00:03:31.210 --> 00:03:32.510
"Wait, what are you doing?

00:03:32.510 --> 00:03:34.140
Why are you all going
to look for gold based

00:03:34.140 --> 00:03:36.430
on these tiny little nuggets?"

00:03:36.430 --> 00:03:39.660
Until you realize that this
is really all tied to the sort

00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:43.400
of personal history of Narvaez
himself who was a contemporary

00:03:43.400 --> 00:03:46.710
and in some sense is a
rival of Hernan Cortes.

00:03:46.710 --> 00:03:51.410
Hernan Cortes, the man who
conquered Mexico had departed Cuba

00:03:51.410 --> 00:03:54.590
without actually securing
any of the proper paperwork

00:03:54.590 --> 00:03:59.580
and so Narvaez was sent in pursuit
of Cortes to try and stop him

00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:01.570 position:56%
and to convey to the Mexican emperor

00:04:01.570 --> 00:04:05.360
that Narvaez was actually
the rightful messenger

00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:07.100
from the king of Spain.

00:04:07.100 --> 00:04:10.590
And so, when he actually
landed in Mexico and try

00:04:10.590 --> 00:04:14.160 position:56%
to stop Cortes, Cortes defeated him.

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:17.810
And not only did Narvaez's
men desert him and join Cortes

00:04:17.810 --> 00:04:22.280 position:56%
but Narvaez lost his right eye in
the confrontation and thereafter had

00:04:22.280 --> 00:04:24.480
to wear a black eyepatch.

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:26.760
So imagine what it must
have been like for Narvaez

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:30.800
to have been the man who was
sort of left out of that big,

00:04:30.800 --> 00:04:34.810
big prize that Mexico was and so
then when he landed in Florida,

00:04:34.810 --> 00:04:40.810
he was in no mood to wait
or to make these decisions.

00:04:40.810 --> 00:04:44.420
So as soon as he found gold, he
decided to send all the men inland

00:04:44.420 --> 00:04:47.980
to look for it and of course
there is no gold in Florida.

00:04:47.980 --> 00:04:54.450
And within a year, there are only
four survivors for this expedition.

00:04:54.450 --> 00:04:57.570
And the reason that we know
about this expedition at all is

00:04:57.570 --> 00:05:01.360
because it was written about some
years later, many, many years later

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:04.710
by Cabeza de Vaca who was the
treasurer of the expedition.

00:05:04.710 --> 00:05:06.510
And it really is the only--

00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:10.680
or the first narrative we
have of Spanish exploration

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:13.910
of North America, so it's a
very, very valuable document.

00:05:13.910 --> 00:05:17.300
And it contains a lot
of ethnological detail

00:05:17.300 --> 00:05:19.940
about some tribes that
are now extinct.

00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:22.310
And as I was reading this
document, I was just really,

00:05:22.310 --> 00:05:25.940
really struck by all
of the silences in it.

00:05:25.940 --> 00:05:27.940 position:56%
So for example, there are no mention

00:05:27.940 --> 00:05:30.490
of any women even though
these men end up--

00:05:30.490 --> 00:05:33.250
the four survivors end up
spending merely a decade among

00:05:33.250 --> 00:05:35.060
indigenous people.

00:05:35.060 --> 00:05:38.800 position:56%
And I was struck by that but also by
the fact that even indigenous men,

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:41.560
there's only one of them
that's mentioned by name.

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:46.750
The rest are known only as tribes
as groups, not as individuals.

00:05:46.750 --> 00:05:52.420
And even this man who I was
really interested in, Estebanico,

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:55.390
he is named-- he is
mentioned about half a--

00:05:55.390 --> 00:05:59.340
I mean, about a dozen times in
the book, half a dozen by his name

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:02.860
or the name that the Spaniards
give him which is Estebanico.

00:06:02.860 --> 00:06:06.660
And the other half by-- he's just
called the slave or the black man.

00:06:06.660 --> 00:06:10.070
And I was just really interested in
sort of that silencing in history

00:06:10.070 --> 00:06:13.810
and how it promoted certain
myths about Spanish exploration

00:06:13.810 --> 00:06:15.990
that it was the province
of white men

00:06:15.990 --> 00:06:18.190
that native peoples
were silent in it.

00:06:18.190 --> 00:06:21.270
And that even the people of
color who were involved were sort

00:06:21.270 --> 00:06:25.950
of cast aside even though this
guy played a really important part

00:06:25.950 --> 00:06:29.850 position:56%
in that expedition in the sense
that he learned indigenous languages

00:06:29.850 --> 00:06:34.010
and sort of became a de facto
translator for the others.

00:06:34.010 --> 00:06:35.860
And so I was really just
intrigued and I thought

00:06:35.860 --> 00:06:38.840
to myself wouldn't it be
interesting to retell that story

00:06:38.840 --> 00:06:41.360
but from the point of
view of this one member

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:45.260
of the expedition whose
testimony was never collected.

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:49.510
The other three survivors actually
had their testimonies collected

00:06:49.510 --> 00:06:52.720
in front of an official body.

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:54.150
But because he was a slave,

00:06:54.150 --> 00:06:56.050
Estebanico's testimony
was never recorded.

00:06:56.050 --> 00:06:59.260 position:56%
And I actually thought that that
perspective was the most interesting

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:04.520
one because he was neither
a conqueror nor a conquered.

00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:05.940
He was sort of an interloper.

00:07:05.940 --> 00:07:08.730
He was someone halfway
in between and I thought

00:07:08.730 --> 00:07:13.810
that that particular position made
him interesting to me and I wanted

00:07:13.810 --> 00:07:16.170
to write a book from his
perspective about this--

00:07:16.170 --> 00:07:17.470
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: Yeah.

00:07:17.470 --> 00:07:20.170
And what you've done is not only
imagine the arrival in America

00:07:20.170 --> 00:07:24.130
but also his entire back story in
Morocco and leaving his family.

00:07:24.130 --> 00:07:27.680 position:56%
And you've completely fictionalized
the story of what must have happened

00:07:27.680 --> 00:07:30.530
as he boarded the ships
and why he ended up there

00:07:30.530 --> 00:07:31.850
and the life that he's missing.

00:07:31.850 --> 00:07:35.850
So it's kind of an interlace
narrative between both arriving

00:07:35.850 --> 00:07:37.150
and remembering the past.

00:07:37.150 --> 00:07:38.450
&gt;&gt; Laila Lalami: Right.

00:07:38.450 --> 00:07:40.280
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: So it's a fully
sort of fleshed out vantage point.

00:07:40.280 --> 00:07:41.580
&gt;&gt; Laila Lalami: Right.

00:07:41.580 --> 00:07:42.880
Yeah, I mean, I wanted--
I thought, you know,

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:45.450
if I'm going to create
this character, there is--

00:07:45.450 --> 00:07:50.180
he has his own life, his
own agendas if you will,

00:07:50.180 --> 00:07:53.980
his own desires, his own ambitions.

00:07:53.980 --> 00:07:56.340
The expedition is part
of that and it's--

00:07:56.340 --> 00:07:59.960 position:56%
the expedition is something that he
swept up in but it's not necessarily

00:07:59.960 --> 00:08:01.830
at the center of his life.

00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:06.120
So in a way, it's basically
moving the center away

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:08.990
from what the other book was doing
and then kind of saying, wait, no,

00:08:08.990 --> 00:08:10.880
here is the story and
here is one way to look

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:12.800
at it that's completely different.

00:08:12.800 --> 00:08:17.000
And the center of that story is
him, he's the hero, so it's really

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.730
about him and how he grew up
and how he came to be a part

00:08:20.730 --> 00:08:23.020
of this expedition and what
happened to him afterward,

00:08:23.020 --> 00:08:24.940
so it's kind of a decent train.

00:08:24.940 --> 00:08:26.620
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: Well, it's
interesting too because I feel

00:08:26.620 --> 00:08:28.470
like you must have
also thought so much,

00:08:28.470 --> 00:08:30.580
you're also a contemporary
columnist and you write a lot

00:08:30.580 --> 00:08:33.950
about what's happening in our
society now but I wondered

00:08:33.950 --> 00:08:37.930
if you also felt that the idea of
returning the sort of vantage point

00:08:37.930 --> 00:08:40.130
and returning the narrative
power to someone

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:44.680 position:56%
like him was also a political act
in a way because in a sense, I mean,

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:46.520
this book comes at a time
when we're talking a lot

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:50.780 position:56%
about who tells a story, why they
tell it and what we don't understand

00:08:50.780 --> 00:08:52.880
when we don't hear it
from this perspective.

00:08:52.880 --> 00:08:54.180
&gt;&gt; Laila Lalami: Right.

00:08:54.180 --> 00:08:55.480
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: I just wondered
if that was informing you to think

00:08:55.480 --> 00:08:59.610
about writing it now in
2014 or '15 when many

00:08:59.610 --> 00:09:00.910
of us encountered the book.

00:09:00.910 --> 00:09:02.210
&gt;&gt;

00:09:02.210 --> 00:09:03.510
&gt;&gt; Laila Lalami: Right,
I mean, I think that--

00:09:03.510 --> 00:09:07.160
yes, the story takes place in the
16th century but I was writing it,

00:09:07.160 --> 00:09:11.980
I started writing it in 2009 and
it would be foolish of me to claim

00:09:11.980 --> 00:09:15.280
that I wrote it only
with the knowledge

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:17.310
of what happened in
the 16th century.

00:09:17.310 --> 00:09:21.440
As the author, I knew so much
more about the story and so,

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:24.680
even though I am limited in
sort of telling the story

00:09:24.680 --> 00:09:27.860
from that character's perspective,
of course the whole idea

00:09:27.860 --> 00:09:29.810
of telling it from
his perspective is

00:09:29.810 --> 00:09:34.980
in a sense creating an
argument with history.

00:09:34.980 --> 00:09:39.170
And I think that-- In general,
I think history is an argument

00:09:39.170 --> 00:09:42.590
so it's basically saying like who
gets to tell the story in what way.

00:09:42.590 --> 00:09:45.200
The facts in the book
are exactly the same

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:50.600
as in Cabeza de Vaca's history
of the Narvaez expedition.

00:09:50.600 --> 00:09:54.440
What's different is the story
built around those facts,

00:09:54.440 --> 00:09:59.490
the things that what glues these
facts together is what's different.

00:09:59.490 --> 00:10:02.610
And I think that that
holds true today too.

00:10:02.610 --> 00:10:07.380
So, whenever we tell these stories,
we're not just talking about facts

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:10.190
but we're looking at a
perspective on these facts.

00:10:10.190 --> 00:10:11.540
So yes, it's absolutely true

00:10:11.540 --> 00:10:13.310
that that was something
in the back of my mind.

00:10:13.310 --> 00:10:14.990
&gt;&gt; Bilal Qureshi: You kept
a pretty interesting blog

00:10:14.990 --> 00:10:17.730
